04949nmm a2200733Ia 9781571137074DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20072007xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815711370747 a10.1515/97815711370742doi  a(DE-B1597)676384  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a831/.6qOCoLC222/eng/20230216  aGK 7009qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/41159:118101 aHodkinson, James R, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen and Writing in the Works of Novalis :bTransformation beyond Measure? /cJames R Hodkinson.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2007] 1bCamden House, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (286 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v1700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations of Major Primary Works Cited -- tTypological Conventions in Novalis: Schriften -- tIntroduction -- t1: Writing in Context: Romanticism, Gender, and the Case of Novalis -- t2: Writing about Women, 1795–99 -- t3: Esteem and the Epistolary: Hardenberg and Women of Letters -- t4: Music and the Manifold of Voices: The Subject and the Theory of Polyphony, 1797–99 -- t5: From Music to Metamorphosis: Women’s Role and Writing in Heinrich von Ofterdingen, 1798–1801 -- t6: “Freyes Fabelthum”: The Poetic Construction of Gender in Hardenberg’s Religious Writing -- tConclusion: Progression, Reaction, and Tension in Hardenberg’s Gender Writing -- tWorks Consulted -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA balanced study of gender in Novalis as expressed in his literary, political, and scientific writings and in his letters.The great poet and polymath Friedrich von Hardenberg, known as Novalis, was long seen as representing a particular brand of German Romanticism, embodying a predilection for the mystical and the irrational and a longing for death.Yet 20th-century scholars debunked that myth and arrived at a view of the poet as one who produced a unified, precociously modern body of work in which human systems of individual and collective being as well as knowledge and itsdisciplines exist as fictional structures, as represented possibility rather than fixed truth. As such, all being and knowledge could and should be subjected to the ironic play of Romantic poetry, which sought to renew the individual and the world it inhabited. Hardenberg's work has come in for particular criticism for idealizing women, thus denying the living, expressive female subject; the conservative social roles it ascribes to women are also cited. Although more recent critics have discerned an empowered female subject in Novalis, this is the first balanced, book-length study of gender in Novalis in English. It concludes that Hardenberg's Romantic writing began to be successful in reinventing the "fiction" of female identity, and goes further to reveal his extensive interaction with women as intellectual equals. James R. Hodkinson is Assistant Professor of German at the University of Warwick, UK.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aWomen in literature. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aFemale identity.  aFemale subject.  aFeminism.  aFiction.  aFriedrich von Hardenberg.  aGender.  aGerman Romanticism.  aMystical.  aNovalis.  aPhilosophy.  aPoetry.  aRomantic writing.  aSexism.  aWomen in Literature.  aWomen's studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978157113707440uhttps://ww